{'ans': 'Binary is a way of representing information using only two digits: 0 and 1. These digits are known as "bits." To read and write binary, you start by grouping bits into sets of eight. Each group of eight bits is called a "byte." A byte can represent a number between 0 and 255. For example, the binary number "10101010" is one byte and represents the number 170. To read a binary number, you simply look at each bit and determine whether it is a 0 or a 1. If it\'s a 0, you don\'t do anything. If it\'s a 1, you add the value of that bit to your total. For example, let\'s say you want to read the binary number "10101010." You would start from the right side and work your way to the left. The rightmost bit is a 0, so you don\'t do anything. The next bit is a 1, so you add 1 to your total. The next bit is a 0, so you don\'t do anything. The next bit is a 1, so you add 2 to your total. The next bit is a 0, so you don\'t do anything. The next bit is a 1, so you add 4 to your total. The next bit is a 0, so you don\'t do anything. The leftmost bit is a 1, so you add 8 to your total. When you add all of these values together, you get the total value of the binary number, which is 170. To write a binary number, you start by determining the value of each bit. For example, to write the number 170 in binary, you would start by determining the value of the leftmost bit. Since 170 is greater than or equal to 128, the leftmost bit would be a 1. The next bit would be a 0, since 170 is not greater than or equal to 64. The next bit would be a 1, since 170 is greater than or equal to 32. The next bit would be a 0, since 170 is not greater than or equal to 16. The next bit would be a 1, since 170 is greater than or equal to 8. The next bit would be a 0, since 170 is not greater than or equal to 4. The rightmost bit would be a 0, since 170 is not greater than or equal to 2. When you put all of these bits together, you get the binary number "10101010."'}
