{'ans': 'Spades is a trick-taking card game played with a standard deck of 52 cards. It is traditionally played with four players, but variations exist for three or six players. Here are the basic rules of how to play Spades:\\n\\nDeal the cards: Each player is dealt a hand of 13 cards. The remaining cards are placed face down in a stack in the center of the table, which is known as the "kitty."\\n\\nDetermine the trump suit: The player to the left of the dealer starts by declaring a suit as the trump suit. The trump suit is the suit that will rank highest in the game.\\n\\nBid: Starting with the player to the left of the dealer, each player must bid on the number of tricks they think they will be able to take during the hand. A bid of "zero" is known as a "nil" bid, and a bid of "one" is known as a "blind" nil. A player who bids nil risks losing 100 points if they fail to take a trick, but if they succeed, they earn a bonus of 100 points.\\n\\nPlay the cards: The player to the left of the dealer starts the trick by playing a card of their choice. Each player must follow suit if they have a card of the same suit. If a player does not have a card of the same suit, they may play any card. The highest card of the suit led wins the trick, unless a trump card is played, in which case the highest trump card wins the trick. The winner of the trick leads the next trick.\\n\\nScore the hand: At the end of each hand, each team adds up the number of tricks they have taken. If a team bids to take a certain number of tricks and succeeds, they score 10 points for each trick bid, plus an additional point for each trick taken. If a team bids to take a certain number of tricks and fails, they lose 10 points for each trick bid. If a player bids nil and succeeds, they earn a bonus of 100 points. If a player bids nil and fails, they lose 100 points.\\n\\nContinue playing: The game continues until one team reaches a score of 500 points or more. The team with the highest score at that point wins the game.\\n\\nThere are many variations and additional rules that can be used to play Spades, so it\'s a good idea to agree on the specific rules with your fellow players before starting a game.'}
